<p>If you write code for a living in India, AI tools have changed your job whether you have used them or not. Junior devs are shipping features in days that used to take weeks. Senior devs are reviewing pull requests with AI as a second pair of eyes. The question for Indian engineers in 2026 is not whether to use AI, but which tools justify their cost in INR with GST.</p>

<h2>Why engineers should pay for AI tools</h2>

<p>Unlike some other professions where the free tier is enough, software engineering benefits more from paid AI. Free tiers have message limits and weaker context windows. For real engineering work (debugging across files, system design, security review), the paid Pro plans are worth the &#8377;2,000 to 4,000 monthly cost.</p>

<p>If you work for a company, ask if they will reimburse it as a development tool. Most Indian product companies say yes when you frame it as productivity software, not a personal subscription.</p>

<h2>The 3 AI tools we recommend for Indian engineers</h2>

<h3>Claude Pro, for code review, system design, and tests</h3>
<div class="tool-card">
  <span class="price-tag">Free tier (limited)</span>
  <span class="price-tag">Pro: &#8377;2,005/month with GST</span>
  <p><strong>Best for:</strong> Code review, refactoring suggestions, writing unit and integration tests, system design discussions, debugging across multiple files, writing documentation, and reviewing pull requests.</p>
  <p><strong>Why engineers prefer it:</strong> Claude's coding output is more accurate on long-context work (whole repos, multi-file changes). The Artifacts feature lets you generate working components, run them, and iterate without leaving the chat.</p>
